title: Icons
description: Icons can be used to represent common actions. Material Symbols are a set of variable icon fonts created at seven weights across three different styles.

Takeaways

• Icons are small graphics used to symbolize common actions, files, devices, and directories.
  • Material Symbols are variable icon fonts, a new font format containing multiple stylistic variations.
  • Stylistic variations that can be dynamically customized include: weight, fill, optical size, and grade.
  • Symbols are provided as a set of static icons generated from those variable icon fonts.
  • They are available as SVGs, gstatic, and icon fonts, accessed via the Material Symbols Figma plugin or on Google Fonts.
What's new

Material Symbols

The new variable icon font set supports three styles: outlined, rounded, and sharp. All Material Symbols are newly drawn to be pixel-crisp and modernized.

Adjustable axes

Material Symbols have four adjustable stylistic variable font attributes called axes. An axis refers to an attribute of a symbol that can be altered to create visual variations. The attributes are: weight, fill, optical size, grade.

Design principles

Icons are an essential element of any interface, packing an informative punch into a small form factor. They’re designed to be simple, modern, friendly, and sometimes quirky. To ensure consistency and readability, their limited size means that each icon must strictly adhere to guidance while still expressing essential characteristics.

contentChunks.footer: Simplify icons for greater clarity and legibility.
contentChunks.altText: Front view of boat icon.

contentChunks.footer: Don’t be overly literal. Avoid complex icons.
contentChunks.altText: Boat image with sails, mast, and flag.

contentChunks.footer: Make icons graphic and bold.
contentChunks.altText: Use geometric, consistent shapes.

contentChunks.footer: Don’t use delicate or loose organic shapes.
contentChunks.altText: Detailed thumbs-up icon with four horizontal sections and outlined lens

contentChunks.footer: Use and maintain a consistent visual style throughout one icon set.
contentChunks.altText: Four icons with a consistent style.

contentChunks.footer: Avoid mixing styles for one icon set.
contentChunks.altText: Four icons in different styles.

contentChunks.htmlValue: Icon sizes and layout

Standard (Baseline) icon size

Standard icons are displayed as 24dp x 24dp. For pixel-perfect accuracy, create icons for viewing at 100% scale.

contentChunks.footer: 24dp grid at 100% scale
contentChunks.altText: Icon at 100% scale on a 24dp grid.

contentChunks.footer: 24dp grid at 1000% scale
contentChunks.altText: Icon at 1000% scale on a 24dp grid.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Additional optical icon sizes

Icons support additional sizes: 20dp, 40dp, and 48dp, with 20dp primarily for desktop, dense layouts, and small scale visuals, and 40dp and 48dp optimized for display or headline type, plus larger screen sizes.

contentChunks.footer: Supported icon sizes: 20dp, 24dp, 40dp, and 48dp.
contentChunks.altText: Four document icons shown at increasing scales.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Standard (Baseline) icon layout

Icon content should remain inside of the live area, which is the region of an image that is unlikely to be hidden from view (such as an area where sidebars appear upon scrolling).

If additional visual weight is needed, content may extend into the padding between the live area and the trim area (the complete size of a graphic). No parts of the icon should extend outside of the trim area.

contentChunks.footer:
Live area
Icon content is limited to the 20dp x 20dp live area, with 2dp of padding around the perimeter.

contentChunks.footer:

2dp of padding surrounds the live area.

contentChunks.htmlValue: Grid and keyline shapes

Icon design template

If your design requires an icon that isn’t covered by the over 2,000 variations in Google Font’s icon library, you may want to create your own. Download this 24dp icon grid and keyline template* (.zip file) to design custom icons in Adobe Illustrator. 

*This template is available under Apache 2.0. By downloading this file, you agree to the Google Terms of Service. The Google Privacy Policy describes how data is handled in this service.

Icon grid and keyline

The icon grid establishes clear rules for the consistent, but flexible, positioning of graphic elements. 

Keyline shapes are the foundation of the grid. By using these core shapes as guidelines, you can maintain consistent visual proportions across system icons.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Corners

Corner radii are 2dp by default. For the outlined style symbols, interior corners are square, not rounded. For shapes 2dp wide or less, stroke corners shouldn’t be rounded.

For the rounded style symbols, both exterior and interior corner radii are rounded and for the sharp style symbols, both exterior and interior corners radii reduce from 2dp to 0dp.

contentChunks.footer: Exterior corners with 2dp corner radii.
contentChunks.altText: Credit card symbol placed on grid with 2dp rounded exterior corners highlighted.

contentChunks.footer: Interior corners shouldn’t be rounded.
contentChunks.altText: Credit card symbol placed on grid with 2dp linear interior corners highlighted.

contentChunks.footer: Overly round corners reduces the symbol’s legibility.
contentChunks.altText: Document icon placed on grid with overly rounded corners highlighted.

contentChunks.footer: Don’t use inconsistent corner radii.
contentChunks.altText: ‘Add more’ icon placed on grid with inconsistent rounded corners.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Weight and stroke

The recommended stroke weight for icons is 2dp or the regular weight (400), which includes curves, angles, and both interior and exterior strokes. Material Symbols can provide a range of weights between thin (100) and bold (700).

contentChunks.footer: Timer symbol shown across a 100–700 weight range.
contentChunks.altText: Weight timer symbols ranging from 100 to 700 weight.

contentChunks.footer: Stroke terminal on an icon.
contentChunks.altText: Arrow symbol placed on a grid with arrowhead terminals trimmed to 45 degrees highlighted.

contentChunks.footer: Counter stroke on an icon.
contentChunks.altText: Add circle symbol placed on grid with linear 2dp inner stroke highlighted.

contentChunks.footer: Use consistent stroke weights and squared stroke terminals.
contentChunks.altText: Add chart icon placed on grid with consistent stroke weights and squared stroke terminals.

contentChunks.footer: Don’t use inconsistent stroke weights or rounded stroke terminals.
contentChunks.altText: Add chart icon placed on grid showing inconsistent stroke weights and rounded stroke terminals.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Complex icon shapes

If an icon requires complex details, subtle adjustments can be made to improve its legibility. These adjustments are referred to as optical corrections. Any optical correction should use the geometric forms on which all other icons are based, without skewing or distorting those shapes.

contentChunks.footer: The paperclip icon uses 1.5dp of the possible 2dp stroke area to fit multiple curves within the 24dp x 24dp icon space.
contentChunks.altText: Paperclip icon on grid with adjusted 1.5dp stroke highlighted.

contentChunks.footer: The ramen bowl icon uses 1.5dp stroke and 2dp stroke together within the 24 x 24dp icon space.
contentChunks.altText: Ramen bowl icon on grid with adjusted 1.5dp stroke highlighted.

contentChunks.footer: Make icons face forward.
contentChunks.altText: Building icon using flat shapes.

contentChunks.footer: Don’t tilt, rotate, or make icons appear dimensional.
contentChunks.altText: Building icon in isometric perspective.

Icon & Material Symbol styles

Material Symbols are the new default, and are available in three styles: outlined, rounded, and sharp. (The legacy Material Icons continue to be available, but don’t have the variable font capabilities of Material Symbols.)

Outlined style 

Outlined symbols use stroke and fill attributes for a light, clean style that works well in dense UIs. The stroke weight of outlined icons can be adjusted to complement or contrast the weight of your typography.

contentChunks.footer: Outlined style
contentChunks.altText: Examples of outlined symbols with stroke and fill attributes.

contentChunks.footer: 2dp outlined icons remain readable across sizes and applications.
contentChunks.altText: Outlined icon set on grid.

contentChunks.footer: For optimal legibility and recognition, some symbols should remain filled, such as full body human icons or proprietary icons.
contentChunks.altText: Four filled symbols showing full body human and proprietary icons.

contentChunks.footer: The lighter stroke weight of these outlined symbols mirrors the thin lines of the app’s typography.
contentChunks.altText: Thin-lined outlined symbols correspond to app typography.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Rounded and sharp styles

Rounded symbols use a corner radius that pairs well with brands that use heavier typography, curved logos, or circular elements to express their style.

Sharp symbols display corners with straight edges, for a crisp style that remains legible even at smaller scales. These rectangular shapes can support brand styles that aren’t well-reflected by rounded shapes.

contentChunks.htmlValue: Customizing Symbols

Material Symbols have four adjustable stylistic variable font attributes called axes. An axis is a typographic term referring to the attribute of a symbol that can be altered to create visual variations. 

Each style symbol contains four axes: weight, fill, grade, and optical size.

Weight

Weight defines the symbol’s stroke weight, with a range of weights between thin (100) and bold (700). Weight can also affect the overall size of the symbol.

contentChunks.footer: A symbol in a range of weights.
contentChunks.altText: Gradual increase of symbols from thin to bold.

contentChunks.footer: 400 regular-weight symbols.
contentChunks.altText: 400 regular-weight icons used in standard navigation drawer and modal navigation drawer.

contentChunks.footer: Don't use the lightest weight for standard-size (24dp) icons. The minimum weight for the size is 200.
contentChunks.altText: Photo gallery using 100 weight icons.

contentChunks.footer: Be careful using excessive weight for standard 24dp symbols.
contentChunks.altText: Three side-by-side 24p standard symbols.

contentChunks.footer: Apply weights consistently.
contentChunks.altText: Navigation rail with consistent symbol weights.

contentChunks.footer: Don’t mix different weights.
contentChunks.altText: Navigation rail with varying symbol weights.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Fill

Fill gives you the ability to transition from a more outlined style to a reversed or more filled style. 

A fill attribute can be used to convey a state of transition, such as unfilled and filled states. Values range from 0 to 1, with 1 being completely filled. Along with weight, fill is a primary attribute that impacts the overall look of a symbol.

contentChunks.footer: Unfilled symbols with fill set to 0.
contentChunks.altText: Unfilled icons.

contentChunks.footer: Filled symbols with fill set to 1.
contentChunks.altText: Set of filled icons.

contentChunks.footer: Bottom navigation with filled symbols in selected and unselected states.
contentChunks.altText: Four filled symbols in selected and unselected states set in bottom navigation.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Grade

Weight and grade affect a symbol’s thickness. Adjustments to grade are more granular than adjustments to weight and have a smaller impact on the size of the symbol.

Grade is also available in some text fonts. Grade levels between text and symbols can be matched for a harmonious visual effect. For example, if the text font has a -25 grade value, the symbols can match it with a suitable value of -25.

contentChunks.footer:
1. At grade 0, the thickness of the symbol does not change.
2. At negative grade, the thickness of the symbol appears lighter.
contentChunks.altText: Symbol thickness at grade 0 and at negative grade.

contentChunks.htmlValue: Grade can also compensate for visual bleed, which is when images can look bigger or smaller depending on the color contrast. To match the apparent icon size, the default grade for a dark icon on a light background is 0, and -25 for a light icon on a dark background.

contentChunks.footer: Icon button featuring a 0 default grade symbol in light UI.
contentChunks.altText: Button with icon and text in light UI.

contentChunks.footer: Icon button featuring a negative grade symbol in dark UI.
contentChunks.altText: Button with icon and text in dark UI.

contentChunks.htmlValue: To make strokes heavier and more emphasized, use positive value grade, such as when representing an active icon state.

contentChunks.footer: An icon with active state using positive value grade for emphasis.
contentChunks.altText: Photo icon in active state appearing bolder.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Optical sizes

Optical sizes range from 20dp to 48dp.

For the image to look the same at different sizes, the stroke weight (thickness) changes as the icon size scales. Optical size offers a way to automatically adjust the stroke weight when you increase or decrease the symbol size.

contentChunks.footer: Four optical sizes, 20dp, 24dp, 40dp, 48dp.
contentChunks.altText: Four icons gradually increasing in optical size.

contentChunks.htmlValue: Traditionally, icons are resized from a 24dp source vector, resulting in a large scaled icon that’s too heavy compared to the original. With the optical size axis, you can maintain the stroke weight (thickness) as the icon size grows.

contentChunks.footer:
1. Material icon
2. Material Symbol
contentChunks.altText: Side-by-side scaling view showing a Material icon and a Material Symbol.

contentChunks.footer: Use 20dp optical size value for dense layouts on desktop.
contentChunks.altText: Desktop dropdown menu with icon in active state.

contentChunks.footer: Use larger size 40dp–48dp symbols when primary actions need to be highlighted.
contentChunks.altText: Forward and reverse symbols highlighted on device.

contentChunks.htmlValue: Using symbols with typography

Pair your type with Material Symbols. Symbols are designed with similar considerations to typefaces, and often appear alongside text. Choosing the right icon set can tie the content of an interface together, enhancing the cohesive branded feel of your product.
Consider some basic rules when pairing typography and symbols.

contentChunks.footer: Don’t use the different weights for Material Symbols and text.
contentChunks.altText: Differing weight of symbol and text..

contentChunks.footer: Use the same weight for Material Symbols and Google Sans family text.
contentChunks.altText: Symbol and text with same weight.

contentChunks.footer: Use the same point size for your symbol and text.
contentChunks.altText: Smaller symbol set next to larger text.

contentChunks.footer: Don’t use different sizes and weights for your symbol and text.
contentChunks.altText: Heavier weighted symbol set next to thinner text.

contentChunks.footer: Shift down the baseline of symbols to approximately 11.5% of the type size.
contentChunks.altText: Symbol baseline set lower in relation to symbol.

contentChunks.footer: Don’t use the same baseline for Material Symbols and text.
contentChunks.altText: Both symbol and text set on same baseline.

contentChunks.htmlValue: Accessibility
Learn more about making your icons more accessible.

Icons with a label text

Label text provides short, meaningful descriptions when symbols are more abstract. This can prove helpful in the case of navigation.

contentChunks.footer: Label text provides short descriptions, especially useful for navigation.
contentChunks.altText: Navigation bar showing four destinations, with 1 active destination featuring both icon and text label.

contentChunks.footer: Use caution if icons are displayed without labels. Icon meaning should always be unambiguous and accessible for all users. Text labels can be omitted in specific circumstances where reduced visual impact is necessary.
contentChunks.altText: Navigation bar with four destinations with only icons, no labels.

contentChunks.htmlValue:
Target size

Adequate space should surround icons to allow legibility and interaction. Symbols of 24dp can use a target size of 48dp.

1. Clearance area
2. Placement

contentChunks.htmlValue: When a mouse and keyboard are the primary input methods, measurements may be condensed to accommodate denser layouts. A 20dp size symbol can use a target size of 40dp.

1. Clearance area
2. Placement
